Original Answer:
B

The reasoning is as follows. The city’s claim is for injunctive relief – an equitable remedy that is properly decided by a judge without a jury. In contrast, the team’s counterclaim seeks money damages—a legal claim that the Seventh Amendment guarantees must be decided by a jury when demanded. Although the parties prefer different sequencing (the city wants its injunction claim tried first to prevent the team’s departure, while the team insists on preserving its jury trial right by having its damages claim tried first), the court has discretion to bifurcate the trial. The proper method is to conduct the judge‐decided equitable (injunction) phase first and then conduct the separate jury trial on the legal counterclaim, taking care that any adjudicated factual determinations in the bench phase are not binding on the jury’s independent fact‐finding in the subsequent phase. That is best captured by answer choice B.
